Review: precise as a fucking razor blade. man, the lengths we’ll go to when we’re convinced something has been stolen from us. what if it was all just a gift?
not even stanley tucci could redeem this
what a fun way to start the year! this could’ve been a dumpster fire but instead was quite enjoyable; they built a world that i loved spending a little time in. good for timothee
snoozefest. so ineffective that i forgot i had read the book until a third of the way through. why was this 2.5 hrs long? and why did all these people agree to be in it? leave this movie behind!

this was okay. an interesting enough watch if only for the style. i miss knowing & loving Anderson’s characters (Tenenbaums is a top movie for me) but also, i guess he deserves to make what he wants these days.
other than being edited like an evangelical summer camp sizzle reel, this fucking slapped and really tore me up. might need to go on a denzel run now.

Movie: Mike Birbiglia: The Old Man and the Pool
Review: more puns than i remember from past specials but mike remains one of the best storytellers of our time. the weaving and callbacks are really just so incredible.

came in with low expectations but honestly this was cute. maybe this is dramatic to say but it made me very nostalgic for all the times i’ve been radicalized and preemptively grateful for all the times to come
okay but—is the grinch a different species?
to be clear—if my dying body was being actively eaten by scavengers, i would want my best friend to interfere with the natural course of the ecosystem & save my ass
